[2] The Lahu does not know the Shan word for \'91cheroot, cigarillo', so he uses the Lahu periphrasis \'9a\'fa \uc0\u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769  \'91little tobacco\'92. He has some of them wrapped up (with other belongings) in a large package, in case it should prove necessary to show the Shan just what kind he wants, but he has not unwrapped it yet .\
\
[3] In this sentence, and in the rest of the text, the Shan speaks perfectly good Lahu. This is just a narrative convention, and the hearer is supposed to assume that he is really speaking Shan throughout. Cf. the convention in American movies where foreigners who are presumably talking together in their own language are made to speak in English so the audience will understand, but with a foreign accent, so that an exotic distance will be maintained.\
\
[4] The words P\'ee-ch\uc0\u596 \u770  y\u596 \u770  \'e0\u660  \'91the Shan (said) to him\'92 are tacked onto the end of the sentence as an afterthought. Such inversions are common in colloquial Lahu.\
\
[5] The Shan now thinks he understands, and recoils in horror. The Lahu word \'9a\'fa \'91tobacco\'92 sounds something like the Shan [sh\uc0\u601 \u780 ] \'91tiger\'92. Perhaps the Shan understands the word \u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769  \'91little thing\'92, which would lend plausibility to his hypothesis that there was a \'91little tiger\'92 or tiger-cub in the Lahu\'92s package, since a big one would not fit. This is not essential to the story, however, since the sequence of vowels u-\u596 -\u603  in \'9a\'fa \u596 \u768 -\u603 \u769 , when rapidly pronounced, sounds very much like the schwa vocalism of the Shan form.}